9,1,beat_00_opening,"You're going to slip. Not might. Not maybe. You're going to slip. And I need you to hear this clearly before it happens: that's not failure. That's the shape of this."\
9,2,beat_01_slip_scenario,"Here's what the slip looks like: It's been a decent stretch. Weeks, maybe. You've been moving. Responding to things. Showing up while empty. The new pattern has been working. Then life does what life does. A deadline stacks on top of a conflict stacks on top of three nights of bad sleep. Someone says something that lands wrong. The weather changes. Something in your body shifts. You don't notice it at first. The weight comes back slowly, like fog rolling in. And then one morning you wake up and the sentence is louder than it's been in weeks. \{core_sentence\}"\
9,3,beat_02_old_pattern_returns,"Your manager asks for your thoughts on something. You open your mouth. Nothing comes. The old pattern is back: Don't speak. You have nothing worth saying. A friend texts. You see it. You don't respond. The old pattern: They don't really want to hear from you. There's something you meant to do today. You don't do it. The old pattern: What's the point."\
9,4,beat_03_voice_returns,"And here's the part that makes it worse: The voice comes back. The one that says: See? Nothing changed. You were fooling yourself. You're still the same person. You're still broken. Those weeks of showing up? They didn't count. This is who you really are. That voice is louder than the slip itself. The slip is a moment. The voice turns it into a verdict."\
9,5,beat_04_what_slip_is,"Let me be very clear about what a slip actually is: A slip is: You waited when you could have moved. That's it. That's all it is. A slip is not: Proof that you can't do this. A slip is not: Evidence that the old pattern is the real you. A slip is not: The end of everything you built. A slip is one moment when the old pattern won. One moment."\
9,6,beat_05_slip_vs_collapse,"Here's what a slip is not: A collapse is when you give up entirely. When you stop trying. When you decide the voice is right and there's no point in any of it. That's different. A slip is a stumble. A collapse is lying down and refusing to get up."\
9,7,beat_06_non_linear_progress,"Progress doesn't look like a straight line. It looks like: You move. You slip. You notice the slip. You move again. You move. You slip. You notice faster this time. You move again. The slips get shorter. The noticing gets quicker. The moving gets easier. But the slips don't stop. They're part of it. Not a bug. A feature."\
9,8,beat_07_paradox,"The paradox: You became capable by accepting you might slip. Not despite the possibility of slipping. Through it. The people who never slip aren't the ones who figured it out. They're the ones who never tried. You slip because you're trying. That's not failure. That's evidence you're doing it."\
9,9,beat_08_both_and,"Here's what's true at the same time: You've changed. And the old pattern is still there. You can act while empty. And sometimes you'll still wait. The new way is real. And the old way hasn't disappeared. Both are true. Not either/or. Both/and. That's maturity. That's what this actually looks like."\
9,10,beat_09_no_false_resolution,"This isn't a story about becoming someone who never slips. This is a story about becoming someone who slips and doesn't collapse. Who notices the slip without turning it into a verdict. Who moves again without needing to erase the slip first. The slip doesn't invalidate what came before. It's just part of what comes next."\
9,11,beat_10_relationship_change,"The relationship to the sentence has changed. Not the sentence itself. The sentence is still there. It still shows up. It still tries to run things. But now you see it. And seeing it changes everything. Not because you defeat it. Because you stop letting it decide. The sentence doesn't disappear. Your relationship to it does."\
9,12,beat_11_bridge,"You're going to slip. That's not a problem. That's the shape of this. The question isn't whether you'll slip. The question is: What happens after? \{teacher_reflective_case_story_2.text\}"\
