recovery_not_dramatic_statement: 'Nobody tells you what this actually looks like.\
\
  It''s not dramatic. There''s no moment where the clouds part.\
\
  It''s just: you stop waiting. And you keep not waiting.\
\
  '\
what_normal_feels_like: 'This is what normal looks like now: acting while empty, not\
  waiting to care again.\
\
  '\
new_relationship_summary: 'The emptiness is information, not instruction.\
\
  Not caring is a state, not a verdict.\
\
  '\
capability_list:\
- You can respond while empty\
- You can speak up while numb\
- You can engage while feeling nothing\
- You can show up while the sentence is still running\
- You can act while empty\
- You can live while feeling nothing\
quiet_confidence_description: 'The confidence doesn''t come from caring.\
\
  It comes from knowing you can move while caring about nothing.\
\
  '\
capacity_building_description: 'Each small action builds your capacity. Not to feel\
  motivated again. To move while feeling nothing at all.\
\
  '\
confidence_reframe: 'Confidence isn''t the presence of motivation. It''s the willingness\
  to act without it.\
\
  '\
framework_summary: 'Notice, assess, act. That''s the framework. It works whether you\
  feel everything or nothing. Whether you care deeply or not at all.\
\
  '\
integration_preview: 'The more you act while empty, the less caring matters. Not because\
  you start caring again. Because you stop requiring it. The emptiness remains. Your\
  relationship to it shifts.\
\
  '\
loud_vs_dangerous_description: 'Everything feels flat when you open your eyes. Nothing\
  seems worth doing when you look at your day. Even people you love feel distant,\
  unreachable. The emptiness sits in your chest like something permanent. Heavy? Yes.\
  Dangerous? No.\
\
  '\
old_identity_labels:\
- The depressed one who can't function\
- The person who needs motivation to do anything\
- The one who can't engage when nothing matters\
- The person who waits to care before acting\
- The one who is defined by emptiness\
paradox_statement: 'The paradox: you became capable by accepting you might never care\
  again'\
progress_description: 'Progress looks like: showing up even when it feels pointless.\
  More days you moved than didn''t. Less time believing the emptiness means you can''t.\
\
  '\
return_statement: 'These practices are always here. This framework is always available.\
  You can always return to acting while empty, whenever you''re ready. The door doesn''t\
  close.\
\
  '\
volume_independence_statement: 'Emptiness is just emptiness. It''s information, not\
  instruction. Not caring is a state, not a verdict. Your depression can be at full\
  volume while you still move forward.\
\
  '\
volume_relationship_shift: 'From: "How do I make myself care again?" To: "Can I do\
  this while caring about nothing?"\
\
  '\
youre_going_to_slip_statement: 'You''re going to slip.\
\
  Not might. Not maybe. You''re going to slip.\
\
  And I need you to hear this clearly: that''s not failure. That''s the shape of this.\
\
  '\
why_slipping_happens: 'The old pattern will always be there.\
\
  Learned over years. Wired deep. It doesn''t delete.\
\
  Under enough stress, under enough pressure, under enough exhaustion\'97it comes back.\
  Every time.\
\
  That''s not a flaw in you.\
\
  That''s how patterns work.\
\
  '\
stress_conditions: 'Under stress, under pressure, when you''re exhausted\'97\
\
  the old pattern comes back.\
\
  '\
slip_moment: 'Your manager asks for your input on the quarterly plan. Everything feels\
  pointless again. The weight is back. The old pattern returns: say nothing. It doesn''t\
  matter anyway. Nothing does.\
\
  '\
pattern_return: 'You skip the meeting. You don''t respond to the text. The emptiness\
  wins. The voice returns: ''See? Nothing''s changed. You''re still broken. You were\
  fooling yourself.''\
\
  '\
slip_scenario:\
  context: 'It''s been a decent stretch. Weeks, maybe. You''ve been moving. Responding\
    to things. Showing up while empty. The new pattern has been working.\
\
    Then life does what life does.\
\
    '\
  stress_conditions: 'Major project deadline, a difficult conversation with someone\
    you love, and three days of functioning on autopilot while feeling nothing.\
\
    '\
  slip_moment: 'Your manager asks for your input on the quarterly plan. Everything\
    feels pointless again. The weight is back. The old pattern returns: say nothing.\
    It doesn''t matter anyway. Nothing does.\
\
    '\
  pattern_return: 'You skip the meeting. You don''t respond to the text. The emptiness\
    wins. The voice returns: ''See? Nothing''s changed. You''re still broken. You\
    were fooling yourself.''\
\
    '\
  trigger: 'A deadline stacks on top of a conflict stacks on top of three nights of\
    bad sleep. Someone says something that lands wrong. The weather changes. Something\
    in your body shifts.\
\
    You don''t notice it at first. The weight comes back slowly, like fog rolling\
    in.\
\
    And then one morning you wake up and the sentence is louder than it''s been in\
    weeks.\
\
    Nothing matters. Why bother.\
\
    '\
  what_happened: 'Your manager asks for your thoughts on something.\
\
    You open your mouth. Nothing comes.\
\
    The old pattern is back: Don''t speak. You have nothing worth saying.\
\
    A friend texts. You see it. You don''t respond.\
\
    The old pattern: They don''t really want to hear from you.\
\
    There''s something you meant to do today. You don''t do it.\
\
    The old pattern: What''s the point.\
\
    '\
story_after_slip: 'And here''s the part that makes it worse:\
\
  The voice comes back. The one that says:\
\
  See? Nothing changed.\
\
  You were fooling yourself.\
\
  You''re still the same person. You''re still broken.\
\
  Those weeks of showing up? They didn''t count. This is who you really are.\
\
  That voice is louder than the slip itself.\
\
  The slip is a moment. The voice turns it into a verdict.\
\
  '\
slip_story: 'You tell yourself: "I slipped. The old pattern came back. I''m back where\
  I started."\
\
  That''s the story. That''s the real problem.\
\
  '\
what_slip_actually_means: 'Let me be very clear about what a slip actually is:\
\
  A slip is: You waited when you could have moved.\
\
  That''s it. That''s all it is.\
\
  A slip is not: Proof that you can''t do this.\
\
  A slip is not: Evidence that the old pattern is the real you.\
\
  A slip is not: The end of everything you built.\
\
  A slip is one moment when the old pattern won.\
\
  One moment.\
\
  '\
slip_meaning: 'A slip means: The old pattern is still there.\
\
  That''s it. That''s all it means.\
\
  '\
slip_as_information: 'A slip is information. Not failure.\
\
  Information that the old pattern is still there.\
\
  '\
slip_definition: 'A slip is: You waited when you could have moved.\
\
  That''s it. That''s all it is.\
\
  '\
collapse_definition: 'A collapse is when you give up entirely. When you stop trying.\
  When you decide the voice is right and there''s no point in any of it.\
\
  That''s different.\
\
  A slip is a stumble. A collapse is lying down and refusing to get up.\
\
  '\
slip_vs_collapse_distinction:\
  slip: 'A slip is a stumble. A collapse is lying down and refusing to get up.\
\
    You''re going to slip.\
\
    You don''t have to collapse.\
\
    '\
  collapse: 'A collapse is when you give up entirely. When you stop trying. When you\
    decide the voice is right and there''s no point in any of it.\
\
    That''s different.\
\
    '\
five_step_recovery_process:\
- You notice it. I slipped. I waited when I could have moved.\
- You don't fight it. You don't spiral. You don't let the voice turn one moment into\
  a verdict.\
- You just notice.\
- And then you do the next small thing.\
- Not to make up for the slip. Not to prove you're still okay. Just because that's\
  the practice now.\
recovery_steps:\
- You notice it.\
- You acknowledge it. "I waited. That's okay."\
- You don't fight it. You don't collapse.\
- You act anyway. Right now.\
- You keep going.\
progress_not_linear_visual: 'Progress doesn''t look like a straight line.\
\
  You want it to look like this: Day 1 you''re stuck. Day 30 you''re free. Steady\
  climb. Clean arc.\
\
  That''s not how it works.\
\
  Progress looks like this:\
\
  Three days of showing up. One day of not. Two days of showing up. One day of not.\
  A whole week of showing up. Three days of slipping. Four days of showing up.\
\
  The overall direction is forward. But the line is jagged.\
\
  '\
how_to_recover: 'And here''s what matters:\
\
  The gaps get shorter. The slips get smaller. The recovery gets faster.\
\
  Not because you stop slipping.\
\
  Because you stop letting the slip become a collapse.\
\
  '\
pattern_of_slipping: 'Weeks of practice 
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  stress 
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  slip 
\f6 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  recovery.\
\
  That''s the pattern.\
\
  '\
starting_over_myth: 'One slip doesn''t mean starting over.\
\
  You slipped. That''s different from collapse.\
\
  The overall direction still matters more than any single day.\
